  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Approximately 1/3 of patients with a permanent end-colostomy will experience a hernia around
      the stoma. In some cases these problems result in the need of surgical correction and the
      risk of recurrent hernia after operative intervention is regrettably high. Preliminary
      investigations suggest a role for primary mesh placement to prevent parastomal hernia. The
      use of a mesh as a preventive measure is a safe procedure. This study will focus on the
      effect of primary mesh placement (two different operative procedures are used) compared to
      patients without mesh placement.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
